{
  "id": "session-1",
  "sessionNumber": 1,
  "title": "Number System",
  "duration": 45,
  "learningOutcomes": [
    "Define rational and irrational numbers accurately.",
    "Represent rational numbers on a number line using division.",
    "Construct the geometric representation of √2 on a number line.",
    "Distinguish between terminating, recurring, and non-recurring decimals."
  ],
  "introduction": "Imagine you have a ruler that only has marks at whole numbers (1, 2, 3). Can you measure exactly half a meter? What about the diagonal of a square with side 1 meter? Today, we will discover that our number line is not just made of integers and fractions; it is filled with 'invisible' numbers called irrational numbers that complete the picture.",
  "theory": {
    "overview": "The Number System in Class IX expands from Integers to Rational Numbers (fractions and decimals) and introduces Irrational Numbers. Rational numbers can be written as p/q, while irrational numbers cannot. Together they form the Real Number System.",
    "keyPoints": [
      "Rational numbers include integers, fractions, terminating decimals, and recurring decimals.",
      "Irrational numbers are non-terminating and non-recurring decimals.",
      "Every point on a number line represents a real number (rational or irrational).",
      "Geometric construction allows us to visualize irrational numbers like √2."
    ],
    "detailedContent": "Rational numbers are defined as any number that can be expressed in the form p/q where p and q are integers and q is not zero. This includes all integers (e.g., 5 = 5/1) and fractions (e.g., 3/4). When we divide p by q, we get either a terminating decimal (like 0.25) or a recurring decimal (like 0.333...). Irrational numbers, on the other hand, are numbers that cannot be written as p/q. Their decimal expansions go on forever without repeating. A classic example is √2, which is approximately 1.414213... and never repeats. We can visualize these numbers by using the Pythagorean theorem to create a length (like the hypotenuse of a right triangle) and transferring that length to the number line."
  },
  "activities": [
    {
      "name": "Number Line Construction Challenge",
      "instructions": [
        "Draw a horizontal number line from -3 to +3 on your notebook.",
        "Mark the integers clearly.",
        "Divide the segment between 0 and 1 into 4 equal parts and mark 1/4.",
        "Using a compass and ruler, construct the length of √2 starting from 0."
      ],
      "durationMinutes": 15
    }
  ],
  "teacherLessonNotes": {
    "sessionOverview": "This session introduces Class IX students to the expansion of the Number System beyond integers. It focuses on defining rational numbers, representing them on a number line, and introducing the concept of irrational numbers through geometric construction (square roots).",
